GloSSH is a permissively-licensed secure-transport stack for ESP-IDF,
created to replace copyleft/commercial dependencies (wolfSSH / wolfSSL).
Both the SSH server and the TLS 1.3 client are built on TinySSH's
public-domain tinynacl cryptography. Nothing here is copyleft.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------
TinySSH  (components/tinyssh/tinyssh)
  Copyright (c) Jan Mojzis.
  Public domain (CC0 1.0 fallback). See components/tinyssh/tinyssh/LICENCE.
  Provides the tinynacl reference cryptography (NaCl/ref10 lineage):
  X25519, ChaCha20, Poly1305, SHA-256/512, Ed25519, sntrup761.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------
glo_mtls bundles a small IETF ChaCha20 (RFC 8439) implementation written for
GloSSH (MIT), because TinySSH ships the DJB 64-bit-nonce ChaCha20 variant
while TLS 1.3 requires the IETF 96-bit-nonce construction. All other glo_mtls
crypto (X25519, Poly1305, SHA-256, Ed25519) calls into TinySSH.

The upstream license text is retained verbatim within the vendored source
tree. THIRD-PARTY-LICENSES.md indexes it.
